response:
Yes! You can use `@weave.op()` on class methods. Simply decorate the methods you want to track inside your class. This works for both regular methods and methods in classes that inherit from `weave.Model`.

Example:
```python
class MyAgent(weave.Model):
    @weave.op()
    def predict(self, input: str):
        # your agent logic
        return result
```

All decorated methods will be automatically traced when called.

Yes, you can place `@weave.op()` before every method in your class. This will trace each method individually. However, if you have many methods, consider inheriting from `weave.Model` and only decorating key methods (like `predict` or main entry points) to avoid excessive tracing overhead.

Example with multiple decorated methods:
```python
class MyAgent:
    @weave.op()
    def method1(self):
        pass

    @weave.op()
    def method2(self):
        pass
```

You're seeing nested `WeaveDict` objects because `dict()` only converts the top level. To recursively convert all nested `WeaveDict` objects to regular Python dictionaries, you need to handle the nested structure.

Try this approach:

```python
def weavedict_to_dict(obj):
    if hasattr(obj, 'to_dict'):
        return weavedict_to_dict(obj.to_dict())
    elif isinstance(obj, dict):
        return {k: weavedict_to_dict(v) for k, v in obj.items()}
    elif isinstance(obj, list):
        return [weavedict_to_dict(item) for item in obj]
    return obj

# Use it on your result
regular_dict = weavedict_to_dict(result)
```

This recursively traverses the structure and converts all `WeaveDict` instances to regular Python dictionaries.

